9.1

  1. Because those parameters have a characteristic akin to the normal distribution: they can take any value from negative infinity to positive infinity.

  2. Because sigma can only take positive values. It can’t have negative ones.

  3. Weakly informative priors are more delimited than vague priors, because the first ones take values that are sensitive to the parameter. It gives a bit more light to the MCMC explorer in that the boundaries of his/her inquiry are more defined.

9.3

  1. b0 would be zero because there is no kangaroo at 0 months. B1 would be positive because age and height are correlated.

  2. b0 would be also close to zero because it is very unlikely to have followers if you don’t commit to anything! B1 should be positive because more activity might give you more visibility

  3. b0 would be more than 0 because it would indicate the number of visitors when there is no rain which is usually an appropriate scenario to visit. b1 in turn might be negative because rain is a deterrent for going outdoors.

  4. b0 wouldn’t make sense because nobody sleeps zero hours. B1 might be negative because the more houors someone sleep the less they would probably watch Netflix.

9.4

Sigma refers to the variability of the data around the mean. Since we want to predict the mean, a higher variability indicates a weaker relationship between x and y and viceversa.

|## 9.5

  1. y= annual orange juice consumption (in gallons) x=person’s age (in years)

  2. Since Y is the annual orange juice consumption and expect certain degree of variability, I will assume it follows a normal distribution.

In a year, the annual orange juice consumption varies normally around a typical value of juice consumption mu and SD:

\(Y_{i}|\mu,\sigma \sim N(\mu,\sigma^2)\)

  1. \[\begin{align*} Y_{i}|\beta_{0},\beta_{1},\sigma \sim N(\mu,\sigma^2)&{\sf with} \mu_{1}=\beta_{0}+\beta_{1}X_{i}\\ \beta_{0c} \sim N(m_{0},s_{0}^2) \\ \beta_{1} \sim N(m_{1},s_{1}^2) \\ \sigma \sim Exp(l) \end{align*}\]

  2. \(\sigma\) can only take values higher than zero

\(\beta_{0}\) can technically take any value.

\(\beta_{1}\) can take any real number, negative or positive. We expect a positive one in this case.

  1. I’ll use the centered version of the intercept because it doesn’t make much sense to assume 0 years in predicting Y \(\beta_{0c}\)

I don’t have any idea about the yearly consumption of orange juice in the US, so I’ll assume a very vague prior. Assuming every single day a person consumes 200 ml of orange juice then the mean would be 200 ml * 365. Expressed in gallons = .2*365/3.78 = 19

plot_normal(19,3)

For \(\beta_{1}\) , we can think that every increase in a person’s age would increase her consumption of juice by .25 gallons but it can as low as .0 or as high as .50

plot_normal(.25,.1)

At any age,I think juice consumption will tend to vary with a standard deviation of 2 gallons. \(\sigma\)

plot_gamma(1,.5)

summarize_gamma(1,.5)

  4. \(\sigma\) can only take values higher than zero

\(\beta_{0}\) can technically take any value.

\(\beta_{1}\) can take any real number, negative or positive. We expect a positive one in this case.

I’ll use the centered version of the intercept \(\beta_{0c}\)

It seems that today’s high temperature will be around 17° Celsius, but since Durham is super crazy with the temperatures, I will assume a vague prior.

\[\begin{align*} Y_{i}|\beta_{0},\beta_{1},\sigma \sim N(\mu,\sigma^2)&{\sf with} \mu_{1}=\beta_{0}+\beta_{1}X_{i}\\ \beta_{0c} \sim N(5000,2000^2) \\ \beta_{1} \sim N(-10,5^2) \\ \sigma \sim Exp(.0005) \end{align*}\]

prior_humid <- stan_glm(
  rides ~ humidity, data=bikes, 
  family=gaussian,
  prior_intercept = normal(5000, 2000),
  prior = normal (-10,5), 
  prior_aux = exponential(.0005),
  chains = 5, iter = 8000, seed=65234,
  prior_PD = TRUE
)

  1. The value of sigma indicates that the estimated posterior standard deviation is of 1572 rides, which is significantly lower than we expected in our prior (2000 rides)

  2. The negative coefficient of humidity indicates that a unit increase of humidity leads to a decrease of 8 rides.

  3. since 95% of the data falls into negative values, we can safely assure that the value of the coefficient is negative. However, we must also acknowledge that there is a lot of variation in our predicted posterior. Here is a plot of all the estimated values of humidty:

df_post_humid <- as.data.frame(post_humid)

9.14

  1. On an average windspeed day, there are typically around 5000 riders, though this average could be somewhere between 3000 and 8000

I estimate that for every unit increase in windspeed there would be a decrease of 20 rides, though this average decrease could be anywhere between 0 and 40 rides

Since ridership is somewhat related to humidity, I estimate that at any given windspeed, ridership will vary with a standard deviation of 100 rides

  1. \[\begin{align*} Y_{i}|\beta_{0},\beta_{1},\sigma \sim N(\mu,\sigma^2)&{\sf with} \mu_{1}=\beta_{0}+\beta_{1}X_{i}\\ \beta_{0c} \sim N(5000,1000^2) \\ \beta_{1} \sim N(-20,10^2) \\ \sigma \sim Exp(.01) \end{align*}\]
prior_wind <- stan_glm(
  rides ~ windspeed, data=bikes, 
  family=gaussian,
  prior_intercept = normal(5000, 1000),
  prior = normal (-20,10), 
  prior_aux = exponential(.01),
  chains = 5, iter = 8000, seed=65234,
  prior_PD = TRUE
)
